/- This is a general framework for working with distributions in a
  way that is agnostic to the specific base field, the specific
  structure of the underlying space, and the specific notion of
  differentiability. It also provides a general formalization of
  vector-valued distributions, which is non-trivial.

  Note that we use `ℕ∞` for the order, rather than `WithTop ℕ`.
  This is because we need a total order for the `at most n` condition.
  The `at most ⊤` corresponds to the usual space of distributions.
  The space of test functions is denoted by `𝓓(Ω, ℝ)`, and its dual
  by `𝓓'(Ω, F)`. The space of locally integrable functions is
  `L(Ω, F)`, and its dual is `Y(Ω, F)`. The space of continuous
  linear maps is `CLM`.

  The main structure of the proof will involve defining the basic
  objects (distributions, test functions, linear maps) and then
  proving their properties. We will also need to define derivatives
  and other operations on distributions.
-/

